text="The Rosolini dominance is not -closed">The Rosolini dominance is not <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot \lnot ]]></fr:tex>-closed</fr:title><fr:taxon>Erratum</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>There is a small error in Section 5.1 of <fr:link
type="local"
href="phoa-1991.xml"
addr="phoa-1991"
title="Domain theory in realizability toposes">Welsey Phoa's doctoral thesis</fr:link>, which we quote below:</fr:p><fr:blockquote><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>, the <fr:strong>r.e. subobject classifier</fr:strong>, be the closure of the decidable truth values <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[2 = {\mathopen {}\left \{\top ,\bot \right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> under countable joins; that is,
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[       \Sigma  = {\mathopen {}\left \{p\in \Omega  \mid  \exists  f \in  2^{\mathbb {N}}.\ p \leftrightarrow  {\mathopen {}\left (\exists  n.f{\mathopen {}\left (n\right )\mathclose {}}=\top \right )\mathclose {}}\right \}\mathclose {}}     ]]></fr:tex>
  It's clearly a sublattice of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex>. Observe that by Markov's Principle, the truth-values in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot \lnot ]]></fr:tex>-closed; i.e.
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\forall  p\in \Omega .\lnot \lnot {\mathopen {}\left (p\in \Sigma \right )\mathclose {}}\to  p\in \Sigma ]]></fr:tex>
  So <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma \rightarrowtail \nabla 2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:blockquote><fr:p>The English prose is correct, but it is not accurately reflected in the second mathematical display, which mistakenly asserts <fr:em>not</fr:em> that the truth-values are <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot \lnot ]]></fr:tex>-closed but rather that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is itself a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot \lnot ]]></fr:tex>-closed subobject of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex>. This is not the case.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>13522</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="machine">#466</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-466.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-005Q</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma \subseteq \Omega ]]></fr:tex> were <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot \lnot ]]></fr:tex>-closed, we would have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma =\Omega ]]></fr:tex>. Indeed, for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi :\Omega ]]></fr:tex> it would suffice to show <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lnot \lnot {\mathopen {}\left (\phi \in  \Omega \right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; because this proposition is negated, we may assume that either <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi =\top ]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi =\bot ]]></fr:tex>, both of which lie in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>I thank <fr:link
type="local"
href="andrewswan.xml"
addr="andrewswan"
title="Andrew Swan">Andrew Swan</fr:link> for explaining the argument above to me.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
